      "content": {
        "id": "79e9303e-50e2-4d39-84a9-bf76f46afa38",
        "contentType": "VIDEO",
        "title": "Labor market is the 'linchpin' holding US consumer spending up",
        "description": "<p>After hearing from a host of companies and top executives this week — including Brinker International (<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"\" class=\"link\" href=\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/EAT/\" data-i13n=\"cpos:1;pos:1\">EAT</a>), Starbucks (<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"\" class=\"link\" href=\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/SBUX/\" data-i13n=\"cpos:2;pos:1\">SBUX</a>), and SoFi Technologies (<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"\" class=\"link\" href=\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/SOFI/\" data-i13n=\"cpos:3;pos:1\">SOFI</a>) — what's the general consensus on the US economy as the American consumer continues to spend?</p>\n<p>Yahoo Finance Executive Editor Brian Sozzi is joined by Senior Reporters Brooke DiPalma and Ines Ferré and Sevens Report Research founder Tom Essaye examine several key factors, from elevated gas prices (<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"\" class=\"link\" href=\"https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/RB=F/\" data-i13n=\"cpos:4;pos:1\">RB=F</a>) and the labor market to same-store sales figures and restaurant menu offerings.</p>\n<p></p>",
        "summary": "After hearing from a host of companies and top executives this week — including Brinker International (EAT), Starbucks (SBUX), and SoFi Technologies (SOFI) — what's the general consensus on the US economy as the American consumer continues to spend? Yahoo Finance Executive Editor Brian Sozzi is joined by Senior Reporters Brooke DiPalma and Ines Ferré and Sevens Report Research founder Tom Essaye examine several key factors, from elevated gas prices (RB=F) and the labor market to same-store sales figures and restaurant menu offerings.",
